recommandationVideos.Description:
The Beatles performing “Hey Jude.”

Hey Jude topped the charts in Britain for two weeks and for 9 weeks in America, where it became The Beatles longest-running No.1 in the US singles chart as well as the single with the longest running time.  

The Beatles did not record their promotional film until Hey Jude had been on sale in America for a week. They returned to Twickenham Film Studio, using director Michael Lindsay-Hogg who had worked with them on Paperback Writer and Rain. Earlier still, Lindsay-Hogg had directed episodes of Ready Steady Go! And a few months after the film for Hey Jude he made The Rolling Stones Rock and Roll Circus TV special that featured John and Yoko but wouldn’t be shown until 1996

To help with the filming an audience of around 300 local people, as well as some of the fans that gathered regularly outside Abbey Road Studios were brought in for the song’s finale. Their presence had an unlikely upside for The Beatles in their long-running saga with the Musicians’ Union in that the MU were fooled into believing the band were playing live, when in fact they were miming for the vast majority of the song. Paul, however, sang live throughout the song.

The video was first broadcast on David Frost’s Frost On Sunday show, four days after it was filmed. At that point transmission was in black and white although the promo was originally shot in colour. It was first aired in America a month later on 6 October 1968, on The Smotheres Brothers Comedy Hour.

recommandationVideos.Description:
Videolla kerron perinteisten kolmen reitin lisäksi neljännestä reitistä mitä pitkin Suomesta on mielekästä mennä Keski-Eurooppaan. Löysin reitin karttaa selaamalla, kun en halunnut aloittaa autoilumatkaa istumalla laivassa 30 tuntia tai ajaa jo hieman tylsäksi muodostuneita Via Baltica tai Ruotsin reittiä. 

Reittivalintaan vaikutti myös korkeat polttoaineen hinnat ja fakta, että meidän autot kuluttaa keskimääräsitä enemmän, sillä pellin alla on 3.5 litranen V6 moottori. 

Toivottavasti tästä reittilöydöstä on myös sinulle hyötyä ensikesän roadtrip suunnitteluun.

- Kustannukset laskettu niin, että lähtö on sisämaasta Tampereelta
- Ajankohdaksi katsottu toukokuun ensimmäinen perjantai
- Polttoaine maksaa 1,80€ / litra
- Kulutus 8 litraa / 100km
- Hotelliyöt 70€ / yö


Via Baltica reitti: 
Autolla Tampere - HKI satama 181km = 26€
Laiva Helsinki - Tallinna = 68€
Autolla Tallinna - Nürburg 2151km = 172€
Reitillä 3 hotelliyötä = 210€
= 614€

Todellisuudessa ainakaan itselleni ei 3 hotelliyötä riittäisi tuolle reitille. 


Helsingistä laivalla Travemündeen reitti:
Autolla Tampere - HKI satama 181km = 26€
Laivamatka halvimmalla hyttivaihtoehdolla = 342€
Hotelli Saksassa = 70€

= 524€

Laivamatka on halvempi jos ei ota ollenkaan hyttiä ja kalliimpi jos ottaa paremman hytin. Jos matka varataan lähempänä lähdön ajankohtaa, hinta nousee huomattavasti. Tässä esimerkissä varaus tehty 6kk päähän. 


Ruotsin kautta reitti:

Laiva Naantali - Kappellskär hytillä = 108,58€
Autolla Kappelskär - Rødby 890km = 71,20€

Autolla Puttgarden - Nürburg = 95,20€
= 524€

Tätä reittiä mahdollista varioida monin keinoin.


Halvin ja paras reitti:

Laivamatkan hinta pysyy kilpailukykyisempänä verrattuna Helsingistä lähtevään laivaan kun varauspäivä on lähempänä lähtöpäivää. Mikäli matkaan lähtee esim neljä autoa ja jokaisessa autossa yksi kuljettaja niin hyttihinta jakautuu neljällä ja tekee tästä vielä kilpailukykyisemmän reitin. Video on tarkoitettu perheille, joissa on Rett-lapsi ja niille, jotka päättävät kommunikaation apuvälineistä sekä kaikille, jotka tarvitsevat tietoa kommunikaatioon tukemisesta.

recommandationVideos.Description:
Sahelin alueen ruokakriisi uhkaa noin 13 miljoonaa ihmistä. Plan Suomi tukee Nigerin lapsia. Toimimalla heti voimme säästää tuhansia henkiä.

Yksin Nigerissä yli kuutta miljoonaa ihmistä uhkaa ruokapula, ja heistä lähes kaksi miljoonaa tarvitsee välitöntä ruoka-apua. Tarvitsemme nyt sinun apuasi, jotta saamme pysäytettyä Nigeriä ja koko Sahelin aluetta uhkaavan ruokakatastrofin.

Vakavaan ruokapulaan on monia syitä. Viime vuoden sato epäonnistui kuivuuden ja tuholaisten takia, ruoan hinta on kohonnut ja tuleva sato on vaakalaudalla.

Plan järjestää kouluruokailuja, jakaa kohdennettuja ruoka-avustuksia, tukee kastelu- ja viljelyhankkeita sekä mahdollistaa lasten terveystarkastukset.

Jo 20 eurolla saamme kuukauden ruoat yhdelle lapselle. Osallistu keräykseen www.plan.fi/lahjoita

Six days deep into the heart of the Sahara, into one of the most picturesque parts of the desert: Tassili n'Ajjer National Park of Algeria, near the borders with Libya and Niger. 

I never thought I could be so overwhelmed by the beauty of the Sahara but for sure this was one of the most amazing trips I have ever had. I witnessed breathtaking Saharan landscapes changing endlessly before my eyes, and I hope that you too, watching the video, will get mesmerized by the amazing beauty of the desert - the tall dunes, the dramatic sandstone formations (pinnacles, buttes, arches), and the ancient rock art. The Tuareg people who have lived in the Sahara for millennia are nowadays happy to guide travelers through its secrets. recommandationVideos.Title: How the Sahara Desert is Turning into a Farmland Oasis - GREENING THE DESERT PROJECT
Keywords: regreening the desert with john d. liu
greening the desert before and after
recommandationVideos.Description:
In the African Sahel a country called Niger bordering the Sahara Desert, the largest desert in the world, is stopping desertification and turning is deserts into an Oasis.

Regenerative Agriculture is leading the way with a technique called Farmer Managed Natural Regeneration or FMNR 
FMNR was pioneered in the 1980s by Tony Rinaudo and Australian Agronomist who is widely known as the forest maker. The innovative technique has been adopted by local farmers through peer to peer learning making it cost effective and easy to implement. Over the last 40 years the visual results and the data have shown FMNR has been extremely successful in turning desert into farmland. It has regenerated 5 million hectors of degraded land, 200 million trees have been restored and has benefited 2.5 million people increasing house hold income by 18-24% the available arable land has doubled since the severe droughts of the 1970s and tree density has 10x since its all time low in the 1980s.

This is an extraordinary achievement considering Niger only receives on average 6.5 inches of rainfall a year and 80% of the country is considered a desert. The country has been effected by severe droughts and suffered huge land loss over the last decades and as a consequence Niger is one of the poorest countries in the world. However Niger has been turning this around, by turning its deserts into a farmland oasis through the technique of FMNR which you will learn more about in this video.

recommandationVideos.Title: Moving to Chernobyl - Embracing radiation to escape war | DW Documentary
recommandationVideos.Description:
In 2014 they fled the war in the east of Ukraine, resettling near the exclusion zone around Chernobyl. Vadim Minsyuk from Donetsk and Yuri Andreyev from Luhansk chose to move their families to the site of the 1986 nuclear disaster, all to escape the war.

Living with the risk of radiation is better than staying in a war zone, that’s the firm conviction of both men. Since the fighting broke out in eastern Ukraine, more than 1.5 million people have fled the self-proclaimed republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, moving to various parts of the country. Some have ended up in the one place that most people would do everything to avoid: Chernobyl. Vadim Minsyuk and Yuri Andreyev are among those seeking to build a new life at the heart of the radioactive cloud that descended after the reactor explosion on April 26th, 1986. Fields, forests and roads were all contaminated with dangerous levels of strontium and cesium.

Near the exclusion zone around Chernobyl, Vadim Minsyuk is now building up his new company. He turns slag, a byproduct of smelting ore, into metal, and earns a modest living. Before the war, he and his wife ran a successful business with revenues running into the millions. Yuri Andreyev ran a successful farm. He spent over 200 days in captivity, held by the separatists. Now he’s once again earning a living from farming, growing sunflowers and food crops. But his farm is also next to Chernobyl’s exclusion zone. He insists his produce is not contaminated, saying he had all his fields inspected.

Because of the relatively short half-lives of cesium and strontium, radiation has indeed decreased over time, says Valery Kashparov, Director of the Ukrainian Institute of Agricultural Radiology. But he says soil contamination could still pose a health risk in some areas. Nevertheless, Kashparov is convinced that the area is ready for a new start. Those affected by the war could be the very catalyst that’s needed.

Australia 4K - Relaxing Music With Beautiful Natural Landscape - Amazing Nature
🌿 Australia, the world's sixth-largest country, is a vast and diverse land known for its stunning natural beauty, unique wildlife, and laid-back lifestyle. From the iconic Sydney Opera House and the majestic Great Barrier Reef to the vast Outback and pristine beaches, Australia offers a wide array of landscapes and experiences. With bustling cities like Sydney, Melbourne, and Brisbane, as well as remote wilderness areas, Australia appeals to both urban adventurers and nature enthusiasts. The country's Indigenous heritage adds depth to its cultural tapestry, while its thriving arts, food, and sports scenes reflect its modern dynamism. Australia's friendly locals, known for their "mate" culture, contribute to its welcoming atmosphere, making it a beloved destination for travelers worldwide.
🌿 As we watch these videos, we can immerse ourselves in the beauty of nature, architectural marvels, and cultural landmarks. The vibrant colors and intricate details captured in 4K resolution bring these places to life, allowing us to appreciate their grandeur and uniqueness.

recommandationVideos.Description:
Videotallenteessa pääsemme tutustumaan, miten kansallisrunoilijan syntymäpäivään liittyvät perinteet elävät nykyään kotimuseossa.  

Johan Ludvig Runebergin syntymäpäivään liittyi perinteitä jo hänen elinaikanaan. Esimerkiksi lukiossa opiskelevat pojat tulivat Runebergin ikkunan alle laulamaan. Fredrika otti kieloja syksyllä kellariin, ja joulun jälkeen hän herätteli niitä kukintoon, jotta runoilija sai nauttia lempikukkansa tuoksusta syntymäpäivänään. Muun muassa tämä perinne elää vielä, ja 5. helmikuuta kotimuseossa on aina kieloja esillä.
